sql:
SELECT DISTINCT customers.customer_name 
FROM customers
JOIN customer_purchases ON customers.customer_id = customer_purchases.customer_id;

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT product_id)
FROM purchase_items
WHERE quantity > 5;

external_knowledge:
- "voyagers" refers to the customers who have made purchases; 
- "bustling metropolis" refers to New York; 
- "shopping ventures" implies that the customers have made purchases at stores located in New York.

- Silent buyers refer to customers who have not given any feedback (no entries in the `customer_feedback` table);
- The term "shopping spree" refers to the last purchase date and the total amount spent in that purchase;
- Spending habits encompass the total spent by the customer across all purchases.

- "cast their nets into the market's waters" refers to making purchases;
- "hauled in more than a thousand dollars' worth of treasure" means spending over $1000;
- "earned a spot on the ship’s loyal crew" signifies earning more than zero loyalty points.

sql:
SELECT customer_id, total_amount
FROM (
  SELECT customer_id, total_amount, ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY customer_id ORDER BY order_date DESC) as rn
  FROM customer_purchases
) AS recent_purchases
WHERE rn = 1;
